      "id": 358628,
      "is_answer_order_important": false,
      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>Pyridine is a flat, hexagonal molecule with bond angles of 120°. It undergoes substitution rather than addition and generally behaves like benzene. Draw a picture of the <i>π</i> orbitals of pyridine to explain its properties. Check your answer by looking ahead to <b>Section 15.5</b>.</p>\n<img src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBaHdWIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--5ded1c934a7d15e8c4987f8afab9dcef7be28158/OChem_15_02_007.jpg\" alt=\"Pyridine has a nitrogen atom in the first position and three alternate double bonds. Nitrogen carries a lone pair of electrons.\">",
      "answers": [],
      "hints": [],
      "formats": [
        "free-response"
      ],
      "combo_choices": [],
      "collaborator_solutions": [
        {
          "images": [],
          "solution_type": "detailed",
          "content_html": "<p>Pyridine has an aromatic sextet of electrons.</p>\n<img src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBaDBWIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--78ba29a303af69392f7ce13992b977f0f454b063/OChem_15_EC_202.jpg\" alt=\"Pyridine has three lobes around nitrogen. One lobe has an unpaired electron and one lobe has a lone pair of electrons. Upper lobe of each carbon has an unpaired electron.\">"
        }
